Gallstone-related cholecystitis: Cholecystitis is inflammation of the gallbladder, which is commonly caused by gallstones. Chemotherapy can increase the risk of gallstone formation, causing cholecystitis.     4. Pancreatitis secondary to chemotherapy: Chemotherapy can also lead to various gastrointestinal complications including pancreatitis.      5. Leukemia-related gastroenteritis: This is a possible cause if the leukemia cells have infiltrated the gastrointestinal tract.     6. Neutropenic sepsis: Severe neutropenia (low white blood cell count) is a common complication of AML that can lead to sepsis if bacteria enter the body.     7. Chemotherapy-induced neuropathy: Some chemotherapy drugs can cause peripheral neuropathy, a set of symptoms caused by damage to nerves that control the sensations and movements of our arms and legs.      8. Bone pain due to bone marrow invasion by leukemia cells.     9. Infectious gastritis/enteritis: The patient's nausea and vomiting could also possibly be due to an infectious cause.     10. Other side effects or complications of chemotherapy: For example, chemotherapy-induced mucositis or an allergic reaction to the chemotherapy drugs.
